{"title_page": "Association for Defence of National Rights", "text_new": "The '''Association for Defence of National Rights''' ({{lang-tr|M\u00fcd\u00e2faa-i hukuk cemiyetleri}}) was a group of [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] [[Club (organization)|associations]] established in 1918\u20131919.\n\n==Background==\nFollowing the defeat of the Ottoman Empire in the [[First World War]], the Ottoman army was disarmed according to the [[Armistice of Mudros]]. Although the Ottoman Empire had to agree to give up vast areas including most of Middle East, the [[Allies of World War I|Allies]] further retained the power of controlling what was left of the Ottoman Empire, namely [[Turkey]]. It soon became clear that the Allies were planning to allocate parts of Turkey to [[First Republic of Armenia|Armenia]] and [[Kingdom of Greece|Greece]]. Parenthetically, southern [[Anatolia]] was put under [[French Third Republic|French]] and [[Kingdom of Italy|Italian]] mandate.\n\n==The national associations==\nThe occupations, especially that of [[Occupation of Smyrna|\u0130zmir]], caused deep reactions among the Ottoman people. [[Association for Defence of National Rights#List of associations|Several]] patriotic associations were formed simultaneously in different parts of Turkey as a result.<ref>Lord Kinross: ''Atat\u00fcrk Rebirth of a Nation'', translation:Ayhan Tezel, Sander Yay\u0131nlar\u0131, \u0130stanbul, 1972, p. 239</ref> The former [[Committee of Union and Progress]] members who were the main opposition to the Ottoman government, as well as [[Turkish nationalism|nationalist]]ic soldiers and intellectuals, were active in these associations and were struggling to have their voices heard by peaceful methods like protesting, meetings, and publishing notices, which were not effective at changing the Allies' policy.\n\n==After the Congress of Sivas==\nDuring the [[Congress of Sivas]] held in September 1919, these associations unified under the name \"Association for Anatolian and Thracen Defence of National Rights\" ({{lang-tr|Anadolu ve Rumeli M\u00fcd\u00e2faa-i Hukuk Cemiyeti}}).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.e-tarih.org/sozluk.php?sd=sozlukdetay&id=27|website=e-tarih.org|title=Anadolu ve Rumeli M\u00fcdafa-i Hukuk Cemiyeti\n|lang=tr}}</ref> This unified organization became the main political force in Turkey up to the end of the [[Turkish War of Independence]]. Its chairman was [[Mustafa Kemal]] (later surnamed Atat\u00fcrk), who would go on to become modern Turkey's founding father. After the war of independence and the [[Treaty of Lausanne]], Atat\u00fcrk proposed to change the name of the organization to the ''People's Party'' on 9 September 1923, just one year after the [[liberation of \u0130zmir]]. After the Republic was proclaimed, the unified organization was renamed to the [[Republican People's Party (Turkey)|Republican People's Party]] (CHP), which would rule Turkey until [[1950 Turkish general election|1950]], and remains one of Turkey's main political parties to this day.\n\n==List of associations==\nThe following are associations that took part in the grouping (with their location or main group component listed in parenthesis).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ataturk.net/mmuc/cemiyet.html|title=Kongreler/Cemiyetler: Kurtulu\u015f Sava\u015f\u0131 Y\u0131llar\u0131nda Kurulan Yararl\u0131 ve Zararl\u0131 Dernekler|website=ataturk.net|author=FORSNET|lang=tr}}</ref>\n*\u015eark\u00ee Anadolu M\u00fcdafaa-i Hukuk Cemiyeti ([[East Anatolia]])\n*\u0130zmir M\u00fcdafaa-i Hukuku Osmaniye Cemiyeti (\u0130zmir)\n*\u0130stihlas\u0131 Vatan Cemiyeti ([[Manisa]])\n*Trakya-Pa\u015faeli M\u00fcdafaa-i Hukuk Cemiyeti ([[East Thrace]])\n*Trabzon Muhafaza-i Hukuku Milliye Cemiyeti ([[Trabzon]])\n*Kilikyal\u0131lar Cemiyeti ([[Adana]]-[[Mersin]])\n*Hareket-i Milliye ve Redd-i \u0130lhak Te\u015fkilatlar\u0131 (\u0130zmir)\n*Adana Vilayeti M\u00fcdafaa-i Hukuk Cemiyeti (Adana)\n*Kozan M\u00fcdafaa-i Hukuk Cemiyeti ([[Kozan, Adana|Kozan]])\n*Anadolu Kad\u0131nlar\u0131 M\u00fcdafaa-i Vatan Cemiyeti (women's organisation)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Turkish War of Independence]]\n[[Category:1918 in the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:1919 in the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:Turkish nationalist organizations|Turkey]]\n[[Category:Republican People's Party (Turkey) politicians]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1918]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1919]]\n[[Category:Anti-imperialism]]\n", "text_old": "The '''Association for Defence of National Rights''' ({{lang-tr|M\u00fcd\u00e2faa-i hukuk cemiyetleri}}) was a group of [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] [[Club (organization)|associations]] established in 1918\u20131919.\n\n==Background==\nFollowing the defeat of the Ottoman Empire in the [[First World War]], the Ottoman army was disarmed according to the [[Armistice of Mudros]]. Although the Ottoman Empire had to agree to give up vast areas including most of Middle East, the [[Allies of World War I|Allies]] further retained the power of controlling what was left of the Ottoman Empire, namely [[Turkey]]. It soon became clear that the Allies were planning to allocate parts of Turkey to [[First Republic of Armenia|Armenia]] and [[Kingdom of Greece|Greece]]. Parenthetically, southern [[Anatolia]] was put under [[French Third Republic|French]] and [[Kingdom of Italy|Italian]] mandate.\n\n==The national associations==\nThe occupations, especially that of [[Occupation of Smyrna|\u0130zmir]], caused deep reactions among the Ottoman people. [[Association for Defence of National Rights#List of associations|Several]] patriotic associations were formed simultaneously in different parts of Turkey as a result.<ref>Lord Kinross: ''Atat\u00fcrk Rebirth of a Nation'', translation:Ayhan Tezel, Sander Yay\u0131nlar\u0131, \u0130stanbul, 1972, p. 239</ref> The former [[Committee of Union and Progress]] members who were the main opposition to the Ottoman government, as well as [[Turkish nationalism|nationalist]]ic soldiers and intellectuals, were active in these associations and were struggling to have their voices heard by peaceful methods like protesting, meetings, and publishing notices, which were not effective at changing the Allies' policy.\n\n==After the Congress of Sivas==\nDuring the [[Congress of Sivas]] held in September 1919, these associations unified under the name \"Association for Anatolian and Thracen Defence of National Rights\" ({{lang-tr|Anadolu ve Rumeli M\u00fcd\u00e2faa-i Hukuk Cemiyeti}}).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.e-tarih.org/sozluk.php?sd=sozlukdetay&id=27|website=e-tarih.org|title=Anadolu ve Rumeli M\u00fcdafa-i Hukuk Cemiyeti\n|lang=tr}}</ref> This unified organization became the main political force in Turkey up to the end of the [[Turkish War of Independence]]. Its chairman was [[Mustafa Kemal]] (later surnamed Atat\u00fcrk), who would go on to become modern Turkey's founding father. After the war of independence and the [[Treaty of Lausanne]], Atat\u00fcrk proposed to change the name of the organization to the ''People's Party'' on 9 September 1923, just one year after the [[liberation of \u0130zmir]]. After the Republic was proclaimed, the unified organization was renamed to the [[Republican People's Party (Turkey)|Republican People's Party]] (CHP), which would rule Turkey until [[1950 Turkish general election|1950]], and remains one of Turkey's main political parties to this day.\n\n==List of associations==\nThe following are associations that took part in the grouping (with their location or main group component listed in parenthesis).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ataturk.net/mmuc/cemiyet.html|title=Kongreler/Cemiyetler: Kurtulu\u015f Sava\u015f\u0131 Y\u0131llar\u0131nda Kurulan Yararl\u0131 ve Zararl\u0131 Dernekler|website=akaturk.net|author=FORSNET|lang=tr}}</ref>\n*\u015eark\u00ee Anadolu M\u00fcdafaa-i Hukuk Cemiyeti ([[East Anatolia]])\n*\u0130zmir M\u00fcdafaa-i Hukuku Osmaniye Cemiyeti (\u0130zmir)\n*\u0130stihlas\u0131 Vatan Cemiyeti ([[Manisa]])\n*Trakya-Pa\u015faeli M\u00fcdafaa-i Hukuk Cemiyeti ([[East Thrace]])\n*Trabzon Muhafaza-i Hukuku Milliye Cemiyeti ([[Trabzon]])\n*Kilikyal\u0131lar Cemiyeti ([[Adana]]-[[Mersin]])\n*Hareket-i Milliye ve Redd-i \u0130lhak Te\u015fkilatlar\u0131 (\u0130zmir)\n*Adana Vilayeti M\u00fcdafaa-i Hukuk Cemiyeti (Adana)\n*Kozan M\u00fcdafaa-i Hukuk Cemiyeti ([[Kozan, Adana|Kozan]])\n*Anadolu Kad\u0131nlar\u0131 M\u00fcdafaa-i Vatan Cemiyeti (women's organisation)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Turkish War of Independence]]\n[[Category:1918 in the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:1919 in the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:Turkish nationalist organizations|Turkey]]\n[[Category:Republican People's Party (Turkey) politicians]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1918]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1919]]\n[[Category:Anti-imperialism]]\n", "name_user": "Aybeg", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Association_for_Defence_of_National_Rights"}
